To find the owner of a form in Office 365, you can use the Microsoft Graph API. Here's an example PowerShell script that uses the Microsoft Graph API to retrieve the owner of a form:
```php
$formUrl = "https://graph.microsoft.com/v1.0/forms/<form-id>"
$response = Invoke-RestMethod -Uri $formUrl -Method Get
if ($response.isError) {
    Write-Host "Error: $($response.statusCode) - $($response.statusMessage)"
} else {
    Write-Host "Form owner: $($response.owner.displayName)"
}
```
In this script, replace `<form-id>` with the ID of the form you want to retrieve the owner for. The owner's display name is stored in the `owner` property of the API response.

You can also pass an additional parameter to the `Get` request to filter by the owner's display name:
```php
$ownerDisplayName = "John Doe"
$formUrl = "https://graph.microsoft.com/v1.0/forms?owner.$select=displayName&$filter=owners/displayName eq '$ownerDisplayName'"
$response = Invoke-RestMethod -Uri $formUrl -Method Get
if ($response.isError) {
    Write-Host "Error: $($response.statusCode) - $($response.statusMessage)"
} else {
    Write-Host "Forms owned by $($ownerDisplayName):"
    $forms = $response.value
    foreach ($form in $forms) {
        Write-Host "- $($form.displayName)"
    }
}
```
In this script, replace `$ownerDisplayName` with the name of the person you want to filter the forms by. The API response will only include forms that are owned by that person. The display name is stored in the `displayName` property of the `owners` collection.
